---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Is LI a Scrabble Word? Yes! (Score 2 Points)"
  description="LI is a valid Scrabble word worth 2 points in both TWL and SOWPODS. It's a Chinese unit of distance (~500 metres). Learn LI strategy for rack-clearing plays."
  keywords="is li a scrabble word, li scrabble, li valid scrabble, li points scrabble, two letter l words, chinese words scrabble, li meaning scrabble"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Is LI a Scrabble Word? Yes! (Score 2 Points)",
    "description": "LI is a valid Scrabble word worth 2 points in both TWL and SOWPODS. It's a Chinese unit of distance (~500 metres).",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-23",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/is-li-a-scrabble-word" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is LI a valid Scrabble word?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, LI is valid in both the TWL (North American) and SOWPODS (International) Scrabble dictionaries. It scores 2 points (L=1, I=1) and refers to a Chinese unit of distance equal to approximately 500 metres or about one-third of a mile." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does LI mean in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "LI is a traditional Chinese unit of distance, roughly equivalent to 500 metres (about 0.31 miles). It has been used for thousands of years in Chinese measurement systems. In Scrabble, it's a low-scoring but tactically useful 2-letter word for clearing tiles and creating parallel plays." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should you play LI in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Play LI when you need to clear your rack of low-value tiles to draw better ones, when creating parallel plays that form multiple words simultaneously, or in tight endgame situations where board space is limited. LI is also useful for hooking onto existing words to create crosswords." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/two-letter-words/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors text-gray-300">Two-Letter Words</a>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Is LI a Scrabble Word? Yes! (Score 2 Points)</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-23">June 23, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>4 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Yes, LI is a valid Scrabble word worth 2 points in both TWL and SOWPODS dictionaries. It refers to a traditional Chinese unit of distance equal to approximately 500 metres. While LI only scores 2 points, its real value lies in rack management — clearing low-value tiles so you can draw higher-scoring letters on your next turn.
      </p>

      <!-- Hero Card -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">✓ Valid</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">LI</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">2 points · L=1, I=1 · Chinese unit of distance (~500m)</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">LI is a traditional Chinese measurement of distance used for thousands of years. In Scrabble, it's a tactical rack-clearer — low score, but high strategic value when you need to cycle through your tiles.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stat Strip -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Points</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">Both Dicts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">TWL + SOWPODS</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">4 L-tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">In the Bag</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">9 I-tiles</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Available</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why Play a 2-Point Word? Rack-Clearing Strategy</h2>

      <p>Low-scoring 2-letter words like LI aren't about the points — they're about what comes next:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Dump duplicates:</span> Holding two L's or two I's clogs your rack. Play LI to offload one and improve your tile distribution for the next draw.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Fish for bingos:</span> If you're holding SATIN + LI, dump LI and draw two fresh tiles. You're now more likely to hit a 7-letter bingo like SATINED or STAINED.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Parallel plays:</span> LI placed alongside an existing word can form multiple 2-letter crosswords simultaneously, scoring for all words formed in a single turn.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">All 2-Letter L Words Compared</h2>

      <p>L has several 2-letter options. Know them all for maximum flexibility:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-amber-500/40 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">LA</span><span class="text-amber-400 text-xs">2pts · Both</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-amber-500/40 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">LI</span><span class="text-amber-400 text-xs">2pts · Both</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">LO</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">2pts · Both</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">LI pairs L with the <span class="text-white font-medium">most common vowel tile</span> (I has 9 copies in the bag). With 4 L-tiles and 9 I-tiles available, you'll have both letters frequently throughout the game — making LI a reliable fallback play.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">LI Extensions and Hook Words</h2>

      <p>LI extends into many common English words for future turns:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Back Extensions</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">LID (4), LIE (3), LIN (3), LIP (5), LIS (3), LIT (3), LICK (10), LIFE (7), LIKE (8), LIME (6), LINE (4), LION (4), LIST (4), LIVE (7)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔗 Front Hooks</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Back-extensions are your primary play with LI — the prefix extends into dozens of common words starting with LI-</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/is-qi-a-scrabble-word/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Is QI a Scrabble Word? The Best Q Without U Play</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/is-ka-a-scrabble-word/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Is KA a Scrabble Word? Yes! (Score 6 Points)</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-50 to-cyan-50 dark:from-blue-900/20 dark:to-cyan-900/20 border border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-300 font-medium">🔤 Check any word instantly — free Scrabble solver, no sign-up required</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
